WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.462 align:middle line:90%


00:00:09.462 --> 00:00:15.438 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:15.438 --> 00:00:25.440 align:middle line:90%


00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:37.140 align:middle line:10%
>> I think Made on Gabriola
to me means made by hand,

00:00:37.140 --> 00:00:41.370 align:middle line:10%
made well, made--

00:00:41.370 --> 00:00:47.030 align:middle line:10%
fueled by creativity,
not fueled by money or--

00:00:47.030 --> 00:00:47.990 align:middle line:10%
I mean, it is.

00:00:47.990 --> 00:00:49.280 align:middle line:90%
Everything is.

00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:50.660 align:middle line:90%
But it's not the main thing.

00:00:50.660 --> 00:00:53.330 align:middle line:84%
Like, the people here
doing art are here

00:00:53.330 --> 00:00:56.570 align:middle line:90%
because they love doing art.

00:00:56.570 --> 00:00:59.610 align:middle line:84%
>> I'm imagining people
who love their homes.

00:00:59.610 --> 00:01:03.860 align:middle line:84%
People in location, in
place, and connected

00:01:03.860 --> 00:01:05.840 align:middle line:90%
to place in interesting ways.

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:10.310 align:middle line:90%


00:01:10.310 --> 00:01:13.620 align:middle line:84%
>> We've branded ourselves
the Isle of the Arts.

00:01:13.620 --> 00:01:19.534 align:middle line:84%
And it's not just about having
a high concentration of artists.

00:01:19.534 --> 00:01:22.370 align:middle line:84%
You know, it's about
having a place where,

00:01:22.370 --> 00:01:26.500 align:middle line:84%
because of the open attitudes
and the casualness of it,

00:01:26.500 --> 00:01:28.930 align:middle line:90%
it sort of fosters creativity.

00:01:28.930 --> 00:01:31.960 align:middle line:90%


00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:37.450 align:middle line:84%
>> And it draws in a lot of
artists and a lot of, again,

00:01:37.450 --> 00:01:41.415 align:middle line:84%
people who want to
feel the freedom,

00:01:41.415 --> 00:01:42.540 align:middle line:90%
if you can call it that.

00:01:42.540 --> 00:01:48.090 align:middle line:84%
You're still trapped
by normal trappings,

00:01:48.090 --> 00:01:51.770 align:middle line:84%
but you just seem to have
more control over it.

00:01:51.770 --> 00:01:53.480 align:middle line:90%
You seem to have more time.

00:01:53.480 --> 00:01:59.700 align:middle line:90%


00:01:59.700 --> 00:02:00.960 align:middle line:90%
>> Rather than making it--

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:03.450 align:middle line:84%
trying to make 100
of the same item

00:02:03.450 --> 00:02:08.380 align:middle line:84%
be exactly the same, which is
the efficient way to do it,

00:02:08.380 --> 00:02:11.708 align:middle line:84%
I make each instrument have
its own voice and be unique.

00:02:11.708 --> 00:02:15.460 align:middle line:90%


00:02:15.460 --> 00:02:18.390 align:middle line:84%
>> You know, there's so many
craftsmen on this island.

00:02:18.390 --> 00:02:20.920 align:middle line:90%


00:02:20.920 --> 00:02:23.960 align:middle line:84%
You know, I was saying to
my daughter the other day,

00:02:23.960 --> 00:02:27.400 align:middle line:84%
I said, the one thing I think
I've learned from living here

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:31.300 align:middle line:84%
is how much integrity it takes
to do the simplest things.

00:02:31.300 --> 00:02:49.192 align:middle line:90%


00:02:49.192 --> 00:02:54.870 align:middle line:10%
>> So Gabriola is a very
rich community of makers,

00:02:54.870 --> 00:02:57.300 align:middle line:10%
of artists and
artisans, and partly

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:00.230 align:middle line:10%
because of the environment.

00:03:00.230 --> 00:03:03.240 align:middle line:90%
This space inspires art.

00:03:03.240 --> 00:03:05.760 align:middle line:90%
It inspires creativity.

00:03:05.760 --> 00:03:08.310 align:middle line:84%
And the natural
beauty of the island

00:03:08.310 --> 00:03:13.570 align:middle line:84%
creates a space for people to
be creative and to make things.

00:03:13.570 --> 00:03:15.900 align:middle line:84%
There's also a very
supportive community.

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:19.330 align:middle line:10%
Artists and makers
support each other,

00:03:19.330 --> 00:03:24.350 align:middle line:10%
help each other, trade
products with each other.

00:03:24.350 --> 00:03:28.260 align:middle line:10%
And so there's a very strong
support network that way.

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:33.450 align:middle line:84%
And then the community at large
values the work that they do.

00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:35.250 align:middle line:10%
Whether they want
to learn from them,

00:03:35.250 --> 00:03:40.290 align:middle line:10%
they want to own and
appreciate and use the items

00:03:40.290 --> 00:03:45.590 align:middle line:10%
that they make, it's supported
on all levels in the community.

00:03:45.590 --> 00:03:49.310 align:middle line:90%
[SCRAPING]

00:03:49.310 --> 00:03:52.440 align:middle line:84%
>> I used to spend my commute
to my desk job drawing

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:54.440 align:middle line:84%
and sketching jewelry and
reading jewelry books.

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:56.492 align:middle line:84%
And you know, I'd get
home and call my mom

00:03:56.492 --> 00:03:57.700 align:middle line:90%
and ask her how to do things.

00:03:57.700 --> 00:03:59.240 align:middle line:90%
And it just evolved from there.

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:04.120 align:middle line:84%
So it started as a hobby
about, say, 11 years ago.

00:04:04.120 --> 00:04:06.850 align:middle line:84%
It had always been in my
life, but never an option

00:04:06.850 --> 00:04:09.930 align:middle line:84%
as a career, and I
really don't know why.

00:04:09.930 --> 00:04:13.730 align:middle line:84%
>> I have been on
Gabriola for 10 years now.

00:04:13.730 --> 00:04:17.740 align:middle line:84%
I arrived here from Montreal to
attend the Silva Bay Shipyard

00:04:17.740 --> 00:04:18.910 align:middle line:90%
School.

00:04:18.910 --> 00:04:20.920 align:middle line:84%
I knew very little about
the island, actually.

00:04:20.920 --> 00:04:23.470 align:middle line:84%
I feel like I was very
fortunate in having ended up

00:04:23.470 --> 00:04:28.510 align:middle line:84%
in a place that was
just perfect for me,

00:04:28.510 --> 00:04:32.910 align:middle line:84%
and it worked out in ways that
I wouldn't have anticipated.

00:04:32.910 --> 00:04:38.500 align:middle line:84%
And a lot of that has to do
with the culture of people

00:04:38.500 --> 00:04:40.190 align:middle line:90%
making and crafting here.

00:04:40.190 --> 00:04:42.880 align:middle line:84%
Which, it seems strange now
to have been entirely unaware

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:46.765 align:middle line:84%
of it, but I kind of walked into
the ideal situation for myself.

00:04:46.765 --> 00:04:51.060 align:middle line:90%


00:04:51.060 --> 00:04:54.323 align:middle line:84%
In a lot of ways, the
infrastructure's set up here--

00:04:54.323 --> 00:04:55.740 align:middle line:84%
infrastructure,
you know, casually

00:04:55.740 --> 00:05:01.930 align:middle line:84%
speaking-- for people to pursue
their craft independently,

00:05:01.930 --> 00:05:04.500 align:middle line:84%
which you don't really see
in a lot of other places.

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:06.960 align:middle line:84%
Or you do, but it's
less accessible.

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:08.700 align:middle line:84%
And something about
the combination

00:05:08.700 --> 00:05:13.860 align:middle line:84%
of being a small community
that's somewhat isolated,

00:05:13.860 --> 00:05:15.720 align:middle line:84%
but we have access
to larger places--

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:20.040 align:middle line:84%
Vancouver, Victoria, we
have the tourist population

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:21.888 align:middle line:90%
that comes in in the summer--

00:05:21.888 --> 00:05:23.055 align:middle line:90%
it makes it all very doable.

00:05:23.055 --> 00:05:28.500 align:middle line:90%


00:05:28.500 --> 00:05:32.370 align:middle line:84%
>> Everything's just
slower here, and yeah.

00:05:32.370 --> 00:05:35.640 align:middle line:84%
We have the time and solitude
to kind of make our businesses

00:05:35.640 --> 00:05:38.060 align:middle line:90%
exactly what we want them to be.

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:42.020 align:middle line:90%


00:05:42.020 --> 00:05:47.140 align:middle line:84%
It's a place where it's easier
to just focus on a few things,

00:05:47.140 --> 00:05:50.800 align:middle line:84%
but just to go deeper
in those things.

00:05:50.800 --> 00:05:53.770 align:middle line:84%
It's easier to
filter out influences

00:05:53.770 --> 00:05:56.110 align:middle line:84%
that you might be
more susceptible to

00:05:56.110 --> 00:05:57.560 align:middle line:90%
if you were in a larger area.

00:05:57.560 --> 00:06:02.415 align:middle line:90%


00:06:02.415 --> 00:06:04.790 align:middle line:84%
>> One thing that I do like
about being on this island is

00:06:04.790 --> 00:06:07.820 align:middle line:84%
that I don't have
those influences.

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:10.910 align:middle line:84%
I'm not competing with,
like, Pandora or all the Made

00:06:10.910 --> 00:06:11.840 align:middle line:90%
in China stuff.

00:06:11.840 --> 00:06:17.780 align:middle line:84%
And my rent would be
higher for my studio.

00:06:17.780 --> 00:06:21.500 align:middle line:84%
My audience might be
higher end, you know?

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:24.560 align:middle line:84%
Like, I can't think of anywhere
on this island where you

00:06:24.560 --> 00:06:31.848 align:middle line:90%
could buy a ring for over $500.

00:06:31.848 --> 00:06:32.840 align:middle line:90%
[SNAP]

00:06:32.840 --> 00:06:36.970 align:middle line:84%
>> So the advantage for
me of being here is, well,

00:06:36.970 --> 00:06:38.560 align:middle line:90%
the isolation, you know?

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:39.840 align:middle line:90%
And you can do it selectively.

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:43.060 align:middle line:84%
If you're not isolated to a
point where you're going stir

00:06:43.060 --> 00:06:45.580 align:middle line:90%
crazy, you can pick and choose.

00:06:45.580 --> 00:06:51.420 align:middle line:90%


00:06:51.420 --> 00:06:53.690 align:middle line:84%
>> I think it would feel
like a job in a city.

00:06:53.690 --> 00:06:56.510 align:middle line:84%
Like, you get up, you take
the bus, you go to your thing,

00:06:56.510 --> 00:06:59.150 align:middle line:84%
you go out and get
your Starbucks coffee,

00:06:59.150 --> 00:07:00.560 align:middle line:90%
and you go to your shop.

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:02.730 align:middle line:84%
Whereas here, it's
like, I don't know.

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:03.530 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, you're right.

00:07:03.530 --> 00:07:06.560 align:middle line:84%
It feels more like part
of a lifestyle here.

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:09.536 align:middle line:90%


00:07:09.536 --> 00:07:14.000 align:middle line:90%
[SCRATCHING]

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:22.960 align:middle line:90%


00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:26.720 align:middle line:84%
I just moved to BC, and I got
my first job at a design firm

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:27.520 align:middle line:90%
in [INAUDIBLE].

00:07:27.520 --> 00:07:29.228 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, what
could I do from home?

00:07:29.228 --> 00:07:31.790 align:middle line:84%
What can I-- and like a light
bulb, I just thought, jewelry.

00:07:31.790 --> 00:07:32.590 align:middle line:90%
Of course.

00:07:32.590 --> 00:07:36.390 align:middle line:84%
Like, my mom's been a
silversmith my entire life,

00:07:36.390 --> 00:07:39.250 align:middle line:84%
for more than 40
years of her life.

00:07:39.250 --> 00:07:44.030 align:middle line:84%
And she knows everything, and
I've learned so much from her,

00:07:44.030 --> 00:07:46.123 align:middle line:84%
just watching her in her
studios when I was a kid.

00:07:46.123 --> 00:07:47.540 align:middle line:84%
She used to take
me to her studios

00:07:47.540 --> 00:07:50.000 align:middle line:84%
when I was two
years old, and I've

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.070 align:middle line:90%
learned how to be a jeweler.

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:54.800 align:middle line:84%
And anyway, so I literally just
called her out of the blue,

00:07:54.800 --> 00:07:57.830 align:middle line:84%
and I was like, Mom, can I
come and just learn from you?

00:07:57.830 --> 00:07:59.440 align:middle line:90%
And she said, sure.

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:06.320 align:middle line:90%


00:08:06.320 --> 00:08:07.640 align:middle line:90%
I'm a purist in what I do.

00:08:07.640 --> 00:08:10.040 align:middle line:84%
I like making
everything from scratch.

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:14.150 align:middle line:90%
I do all my own designs.

00:08:14.150 --> 00:08:17.870 align:middle line:84%
I use traditional methods of
silversmithing and traditional

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:19.830 align:middle line:90%
tools.

00:08:19.830 --> 00:08:21.980 align:middle line:84%
And the process of
traditional silversmithing

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:24.230 align:middle line:84%
has really not changed
in hundreds of years.

00:08:24.230 --> 00:08:28.850 align:middle line:84%
We're still using the same kinds
of tools and same techniques

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:30.090 align:middle line:90%
as they did in the old days.

00:08:30.090 --> 00:08:35.159 align:middle line:84%
And actually, traditionally, the
silversmithing was a man's job.

00:08:35.159 --> 00:08:38.179 align:middle line:84%
Women doing that, it's
kind of a new thing.

00:08:38.179 --> 00:08:43.360 align:middle line:90%


00:08:43.360 --> 00:08:45.235 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot of blood
and blisters involved.

00:08:45.235 --> 00:08:46.810 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:46.810 --> 00:08:48.970 align:middle line:84%
We go through a
lot of Band-Aids.

00:08:48.970 --> 00:08:50.560 align:middle line:84%
Definitely have a
lot of injuries.

00:08:50.560 --> 00:08:51.667 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGH]

00:08:51.667 --> 00:08:52.750 align:middle line:90%
But it comes with the job.

00:08:52.750 --> 00:08:54.010 align:middle line:90%
I'll never have a nice nails.

00:08:54.010 --> 00:08:59.020 align:middle line:90%


00:08:59.020 --> 00:09:02.320 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot of
sensory, tactile parts

00:09:02.320 --> 00:09:03.190 align:middle line:90%
to silversmithing.

00:09:03.190 --> 00:09:05.500 align:middle line:84%
And I know, like,
the amount of tension

00:09:05.500 --> 00:09:08.380 align:middle line:84%
that I have to put on something
to bend it to a certain form

00:09:08.380 --> 00:09:11.680 align:middle line:84%
or to pinch something
together or to hammer.

00:09:11.680 --> 00:09:16.710 align:middle line:90%


00:09:16.710 --> 00:09:21.905 align:middle line:84%
I like the big,
heavy-duty torch.

00:09:21.905 --> 00:09:23.390 align:middle line:90%
The big guns.

00:09:23.390 --> 00:09:28.340 align:middle line:90%


00:09:28.340 --> 00:09:33.070 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot of sounds in
soldering like the torch going

00:09:33.070 --> 00:09:35.080 align:middle line:90%
on like that and the sound--

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:35.980 align:middle line:90%
[POP]

00:09:35.980 --> 00:09:37.120 align:middle line:90%
--of the torch starting.

00:09:37.120 --> 00:09:40.090 align:middle line:84%
When I started making
jewelry, those sounds--

00:09:40.090 --> 00:09:42.130 align:middle line:84%
totally, it brought
back memories

00:09:42.130 --> 00:09:45.850 align:middle line:84%
of my childhood and listening
to my mom do her silversmithing.

00:09:45.850 --> 00:09:48.880 align:middle line:84%
The pop of the torch and
the hiss of the flame,

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:51.700 align:middle line:90%
they're etched in my memory.

00:09:51.700 --> 00:09:55.930 align:middle line:90%


00:09:55.930 --> 00:09:59.195 align:middle line:90%
[HAMMERING]

00:09:59.195 --> 00:10:01.070 align:middle line:84%
And this-- I'll show
you the next cool sound.

00:10:01.070 --> 00:10:02.014 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGH]

00:10:02.014 --> 00:10:03.170 align:middle line:90%


00:10:03.170 --> 00:10:03.970 align:middle line:90%
The acid.

00:10:03.970 --> 00:10:04.850 align:middle line:90%
[SWISH]

00:10:04.850 --> 00:10:05.263 align:middle line:90%


00:10:05.263 --> 00:10:07.180 align:middle line:84%
Well, actually, that was
pretty anticlimactic.

00:10:07.180 --> 00:10:09.590 align:middle line:84%
But when you put a big piece
that's really hot, it goes--

00:10:09.590 --> 00:10:10.472 align:middle line:90%
[HISS]

00:10:10.472 --> 00:10:12.677 align:middle line:90%


00:10:12.677 --> 00:10:14.700 align:middle line:84%
So this is the sound
that I like right here.

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:15.500 align:middle line:90%
[HISS]

00:10:15.500 --> 00:10:16.700 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGH]

00:10:16.700 --> 00:10:18.005 align:middle line:90%


00:10:18.005 --> 00:10:19.520 align:middle line:90%
That sound brings back memories.

00:10:19.520 --> 00:10:23.384 align:middle line:90%


00:10:23.384 --> 00:10:25.820 align:middle line:84%
It's like the smell of drywall,
it reminds me of my dad.

00:10:25.820 --> 00:10:26.620 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGH]

00:10:26.620 --> 00:10:28.330 align:middle line:90%
And the sound of like--

00:10:28.330 --> 00:10:31.090 align:middle line:84%
it's called quenching, the sound
of quenching reminds me of him.

00:10:31.090 --> 00:10:36.470 align:middle line:90%


00:10:36.470 --> 00:10:37.270 align:middle line:90%
I like this part.

00:10:37.270 --> 00:10:42.450 align:middle line:84%
I feel proud to be a
woman who can use tools.

00:10:42.450 --> 00:10:46.140 align:middle line:84%
I just-- I feel
pretty honored to have

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:49.768 align:middle line:84%
been given this knowledge
from my mother, of all people.

00:10:49.768 --> 00:10:53.950 align:middle line:90%


00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:58.007 align:middle line:84%
My daughter once said to
me, I said [INAUDIBLE] babe.

00:10:58.007 --> 00:10:59.090 align:middle line:90%
I've been working all day.

00:10:59.090 --> 00:10:59.890 align:middle line:90%
I'm tired.

00:10:59.890 --> 00:11:01.220 align:middle line:90%
And she goes, you don't work.

00:11:01.220 --> 00:11:02.137 align:middle line:90%
You just make jewelry.

00:11:02.137 --> 00:11:03.250 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGH]

00:11:03.250 --> 00:11:04.050 align:middle line:90%


00:11:04.050 --> 00:11:05.900 align:middle line:84%
But I mean, sometimes
I feel like that.

00:11:05.900 --> 00:11:06.860 align:middle line:90%
I said, yeah.

00:11:06.860 --> 00:11:08.120 align:middle line:90%
I just make jewelry.

00:11:08.120 --> 00:11:10.760 align:middle line:90%
I play all day.

00:11:10.760 --> 00:11:16.616 align:middle line:90%
[DRILLING]

00:11:16.616 --> 00:11:18.815 align:middle line:90%


00:11:18.815 --> 00:11:24.840 align:middle line:84%
The seasons influence
the way I work, for sure.

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:27.930 align:middle line:84%
A lot of it has to do
with the rhythms of just

00:11:27.930 --> 00:11:31.070 align:middle line:90%
busyness, tourist traffic.

00:11:31.070 --> 00:11:34.410 align:middle line:84%
You know, fall and
winter are more

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:36.390 align:middle line:84%
contemplative than
the summer, so there

00:11:36.390 --> 00:11:40.463 align:middle line:84%
are opportunities to sort
of relax and try new things.

00:11:40.463 --> 00:11:41.880 align:middle line:84%
But really, what
you're focused on

00:11:41.880 --> 00:11:43.547 align:middle line:84%
is production, because
you're gearing up

00:11:43.547 --> 00:11:46.350 align:middle line:90%
for a very busy season.

00:11:46.350 --> 00:11:48.930 align:middle line:84%
Summer is very bustling,
busy, so you tend

00:11:48.930 --> 00:11:50.670 align:middle line:90%
to do more repetitive tasks.

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:54.210 align:middle line:84%
There's not a lot of time
to explore new things.

00:11:54.210 --> 00:11:57.850 align:middle line:84%
And that wonderful period after
Christmas when your last craft

00:11:57.850 --> 00:12:00.550 align:middle line:84%
show is done and you've had
a chance to reboot, you know,

00:12:00.550 --> 00:12:02.470 align:middle line:84%
those next several
months tend to be

00:12:02.470 --> 00:12:04.120 align:middle line:84%
the time where you
work on new things

00:12:04.120 --> 00:12:07.522 align:middle line:90%
and try to develop new skills.

00:12:07.522 --> 00:12:10.366 align:middle line:90%
[DRILLING]

00:12:10.366 --> 00:12:13.530 align:middle line:90%


00:12:13.530 --> 00:12:17.720 align:middle line:84%
>> The Gabriola Thanksgiving
Studio Tour is a self-guided

00:12:17.720 --> 00:12:24.230 align:middle line:84%
tour of artists studios where
people can pick up a brochure,

00:12:24.230 --> 00:12:28.730 align:middle line:84%
look at a map of the island
that shows where artists

00:12:28.730 --> 00:12:32.990 align:middle line:84%
and artisans are doing their
work and displaying and selling

00:12:32.990 --> 00:12:34.440 align:middle line:90%
their work.

00:12:34.440 --> 00:12:37.190 align:middle line:10%
Get in the car and drive
around and visit those artists.

00:12:37.190 --> 00:12:41.275 align:middle line:84%
Talk to those artists,
look at their tools.

00:12:41.275 --> 00:12:43.400 align:middle line:84%
Many of them are actually
demonstrating their work,

00:12:43.400 --> 00:12:49.170 align:middle line:84%
so you can stay and watch
them create a piece.

00:12:49.170 --> 00:12:50.134 align:middle line:90%
>> All right.

00:12:50.134 --> 00:12:51.580 align:middle line:90%
So we're done with it on here.

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:53.990 align:middle line:84%
We're going to take
it off the plate

00:12:53.990 --> 00:12:55.918 align:middle line:90%
and put it onto a punting.

00:12:55.918 --> 00:12:58.502 align:middle line:90%


00:12:58.502 --> 00:13:00.960 align:middle line:84%
>> And then you can get in the
car and move on to the next.

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:02.540 align:middle line:90%
And so you can see--

00:13:02.540 --> 00:13:06.630 align:middle line:84%
in a weekend, you can see
jewelers, potters, and carvers,

00:13:06.630 --> 00:13:11.030 align:middle line:84%
and painters, and
glass blowers, all

00:13:11.030 --> 00:13:16.253 align:middle line:84%
talking about
making their works.

00:13:16.253 --> 00:13:20.229 align:middle line:90%
[BIRD CHIRPING]

00:13:20.229 --> 00:13:52.540 align:middle line:90%


00:13:52.540 --> 00:13:53.860 align:middle line:90%
>> I don't really feel like--

00:13:53.860 --> 00:13:54.670 align:middle line:90%
yeah.

00:13:54.670 --> 00:13:59.280 align:middle line:84%
I don't really feel like I don't
live on Gab, because I'm here

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:00.080 align:middle line:90%
all the time.

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:06.410 align:middle line:90%


00:14:06.410 --> 00:14:11.380 align:middle line:84%
I moved here because it
was quiet and beautiful and

00:14:11.380 --> 00:14:13.240 align:middle line:90%
inexpensive.

00:14:13.240 --> 00:14:16.750 align:middle line:84%
And I had been living on the
road and living in big cities,

00:14:16.750 --> 00:14:20.290 align:middle line:84%
and living in the
world of musician,

00:14:20.290 --> 00:14:23.080 align:middle line:90%
of being a touring musician.

00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:27.704 align:middle line:84%
And to me, the fact that
it was quiet and beautiful

00:14:27.704 --> 00:14:32.700 align:middle line:84%
and natural and undeveloped
and inexpensive to live

00:14:32.700 --> 00:14:34.158 align:middle line:90%
was why I moved here.

00:14:34.158 --> 00:14:37.616 align:middle line:90%


00:14:37.616 --> 00:14:41.895 align:middle line:84%
Well, I built this
shop to do what I do.

00:14:41.895 --> 00:14:46.460 align:middle line:90%
And it's my home, Gabriola.

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:51.458 align:middle line:90%


00:14:51.458 --> 00:14:52.750 align:middle line:90%
This is where I fit in somehow.

00:14:52.750 --> 00:14:57.800 align:middle line:90%


00:14:57.800 --> 00:14:59.560 align:middle line:90%
But I don't know--

00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:04.742 align:middle line:84%
you know, the question
comes up about living in--

00:15:04.742 --> 00:15:06.450 align:middle line:84%
do you live where
you're awake, or do you

00:15:06.450 --> 00:15:08.194 align:middle line:90%
live where you're asleep?

00:15:08.194 --> 00:15:09.118 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:15:09.118 --> 00:15:12.820 align:middle line:90%


00:15:12.820 --> 00:15:16.945 align:middle line:84%
I spend my conscious time
on Gabriola, doing this.

00:15:16.945 --> 00:15:22.100 align:middle line:90%


00:15:22.100 --> 00:15:22.900 align:middle line:90%
That's what I do.

00:15:22.900 --> 00:15:23.700 align:middle line:90%
I don't know.

00:15:23.700 --> 00:15:25.990 align:middle line:84%
This is just-- seems
to belong here.

00:15:25.990 --> 00:15:29.627 align:middle line:90%


00:15:29.627 --> 00:15:30.427 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:15:30.427 --> 00:15:34.380 align:middle line:90%


00:15:34.380 --> 00:15:37.340 align:middle line:84%
I'm not all that crazy
about talking about myself,

00:15:37.340 --> 00:15:42.020 align:middle line:84%
but you know, what
we are talking about,

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:46.565 align:middle line:84%
like the things about the slow
movement and respecting craft

00:15:46.565 --> 00:15:48.620 align:middle line:84%
and things like
that, I'm actually

00:15:48.620 --> 00:15:49.860 align:middle line:90%
really passionate about that.

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:55.170 align:middle line:90%


00:15:55.170 --> 00:15:59.385 align:middle line:84%
This commission is actually
really, really special to me

00:15:59.385 --> 00:16:00.385 align:middle line:90%
for a number of reasons.

00:16:00.385 --> 00:16:02.900 align:middle line:90%


00:16:02.900 --> 00:16:07.030 align:middle line:84%
The man who commissioned
it, he heard

00:16:07.030 --> 00:16:10.660 align:middle line:84%
another one of this
model, but he's never

00:16:10.660 --> 00:16:13.000 align:middle line:90%
seen one, because he's blind.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:17.020 align:middle line:84%
So for me, this is
very special for me,

00:16:17.020 --> 00:16:22.100 align:middle line:84%
because his interest in it is
a lot of what my interest is,

00:16:22.100 --> 00:16:26.080 align:middle line:84%
is how it sounds and how
it feels and how it smells.

00:16:26.080 --> 00:16:27.620 align:middle line:90%
And you know, it's tactile.

00:16:27.620 --> 00:16:29.890 align:middle line:90%
It's balance.

00:16:29.890 --> 00:16:32.680 align:middle line:84%
And one of the
things that is very--

00:16:32.680 --> 00:16:34.840 align:middle line:84%
even more kind of
poignant for me

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:39.940 align:middle line:84%
is that it's kind of a miracle
of modern art ophthalmology

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:43.153 align:middle line:84%
that I actually can see at
all, which is really amazing.

00:16:43.153 --> 00:16:45.290 align:middle line:90%
[GUITAR]

00:16:45.290 --> 00:16:46.090 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:16:46.090 --> 00:16:50.680 align:middle line:84%
So this instrument is
designed and made on Gabriola.

00:16:50.680 --> 00:16:52.810 align:middle line:90%
It's a Gabriola [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:52.810 --> 00:16:57.940 align:middle line:84%
And it's got red cedar,
ancient red cedar belly

00:16:57.940 --> 00:17:03.280 align:middle line:84%
and what we call yellow
cedar back and ribs, all

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:07.630 align:middle line:84%
from very ancient wood, and
all salvaged from the beach.

00:17:07.630 --> 00:17:12.880 align:middle line:84%
And then the neck is made of
true cedar, which they call

00:17:12.880 --> 00:17:14.920 align:middle line:90%
Cuban cedar or Honduran cedar.

00:17:14.920 --> 00:17:16.760 align:middle line:90%
[GUITAR]

00:17:16.760 --> 00:17:20.109 align:middle line:90%
So three cedar.

00:17:20.109 --> 00:17:28.180 align:middle line:84%
So one of the things that being
an artisan, it teaches you,

00:17:28.180 --> 00:17:30.900 align:middle line:90%
is respect.

00:17:30.900 --> 00:17:32.890 align:middle line:84%
And it teaches you respect
for the people that

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:34.570 align:middle line:90%
came before you in your craft.

00:17:34.570 --> 00:17:37.650 align:middle line:90%


00:17:37.650 --> 00:17:41.170 align:middle line:84%
You had a question
about artisans.

00:17:41.170 --> 00:17:43.120 align:middle line:90%
What is the value of an artisan?

00:17:43.120 --> 00:17:48.410 align:middle line:84%
I mean, part of it, it's the
distillation of knowledge

00:17:48.410 --> 00:17:52.430 align:middle line:90%
and technique and awareness.

00:17:52.430 --> 00:17:57.100 align:middle line:84%
And I mean, I think it's a value
to society to have people that

00:17:57.100 --> 00:18:00.115 align:middle line:90%
preserve traditional culture.

00:18:00.115 --> 00:18:05.090 align:middle line:90%


00:18:05.090 --> 00:18:06.680 align:middle line:84%
There's a few
reasons why what I do

00:18:06.680 --> 00:18:14.600 align:middle line:84%
is really impractical,
because it's slow

00:18:14.600 --> 00:18:17.180 align:middle line:90%
and it's really holistic.

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:21.800 align:middle line:84%
But there are a few
reasons why it's actually

00:18:21.800 --> 00:18:31.610 align:middle line:84%
kind of valuable, in that
because I'm not industrial,

00:18:31.610 --> 00:18:35.950 align:middle line:84%
I can use a lot of the material
that the industry overlooks.

00:18:35.950 --> 00:18:39.890 align:middle line:84%
I can actually make
an entire guitar out

00:18:39.890 --> 00:18:41.750 align:middle line:84%
of the dumpster of
a guitar factory.

00:18:41.750 --> 00:18:47.190 align:middle line:90%


00:18:47.190 --> 00:18:49.830 align:middle line:84%
The holistic technology--
and I approach it-- this

00:18:49.830 --> 00:18:51.540 align:middle line:90%
is kind of my approach.

00:18:51.540 --> 00:18:54.150 align:middle line:84%
I start with materials
that I salvage,

00:18:54.150 --> 00:18:58.200 align:middle line:84%
and then I bring that to a point
where it's a finished product.

00:18:58.200 --> 00:18:59.830 align:middle line:84%
I know where the
materials come from,

00:18:59.830 --> 00:19:04.290 align:middle line:84%
how they were sourced,
what they are.

00:19:04.290 --> 00:19:08.100 align:middle line:84%
And then, you know, you do the
process all the way through.

00:19:08.100 --> 00:19:13.040 align:middle line:84%
And I do it in a very
slow, low footprint.

00:19:13.040 --> 00:19:16.350 align:middle line:90%
Very low destructive element.

00:19:16.350 --> 00:19:17.280 align:middle line:90%
You know what I mean.

00:19:17.280 --> 00:19:18.950 align:middle line:90%
I don't have--

00:19:18.950 --> 00:19:21.920 align:middle line:90%
I do primarily by hand.

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:23.930 align:middle line:84%
I don't use toxic
chemicals in my finishes.

00:19:23.930 --> 00:19:29.702 align:middle line:90%
[GUITAR]

00:19:29.702 --> 00:19:32.760 align:middle line:90%


00:19:32.760 --> 00:19:33.560 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:19:33.560 --> 00:19:35.840 align:middle line:84%
So I mean, it's a little
hard to change gears

00:19:35.840 --> 00:19:39.650 align:middle line:84%
from planes to guitars, but
that's what that's about.

00:19:39.650 --> 00:19:44.141 align:middle line:90%


00:19:44.141 --> 00:19:50.129 align:middle line:90%
[RAINFALL]

00:19:50.129 --> 00:19:54.140 align:middle line:90%


00:19:54.140 --> 00:19:55.810 align:middle line:84%
>> I don't make
things with my hands.

00:19:55.810 --> 00:19:58.930 align:middle line:90%


00:19:58.930 --> 00:20:00.370 align:middle line:10%
I make things with words.

00:20:00.370 --> 00:20:01.900 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGH]

00:20:01.900 --> 00:20:08.800 align:middle line:84%
I think there's a real need,
a desire for authenticity

00:20:08.800 --> 00:20:11.020 align:middle line:90%
and for the non-reproducible.

00:20:11.020 --> 00:20:14.050 align:middle line:84%
And I think that
as people, as we

00:20:14.050 --> 00:20:17.500 align:middle line:84%
start to fear that maybe
our own subjectivity,

00:20:17.500 --> 00:20:22.540 align:middle line:84%
our own way of being is becoming
more and more like these mass

00:20:22.540 --> 00:20:25.600 align:middle line:84%
produced, easily reproduced
objects, that we're becoming,

00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:27.770 align:middle line:90%
like, easily reproduced people.

00:20:27.770 --> 00:20:31.810 align:middle line:84%
And one of the ways we might
try to resist that or correct

00:20:31.810 --> 00:20:34.270 align:middle line:84%
that relation is to
surround ourselves

00:20:34.270 --> 00:20:36.700 align:middle line:90%
with handmade objects.

00:20:36.700 --> 00:20:38.620 align:middle line:90%
[DRILLING]

00:20:38.620 --> 00:20:43.540 align:middle line:84%
There's a return
to a kind of desire

00:20:43.540 --> 00:20:48.790 align:middle line:84%
or a wish to encounter
handmade objects.

00:20:48.790 --> 00:20:52.810 align:middle line:84%
And I think that
that's definitely

00:20:52.810 --> 00:20:58.540 align:middle line:84%
a response to
oversaturation with mass

00:20:58.540 --> 00:21:02.240 align:middle line:90%
produced, cheap commodities.

00:21:02.240 --> 00:21:10.780 align:middle line:90%


00:21:10.780 --> 00:21:13.345 align:middle line:84%
There's definitely something
about an intentionality, right?

00:21:13.345 --> 00:21:15.220 align:middle line:84%
For me, and I think for
a lot of other people

00:21:15.220 --> 00:21:18.550 align:middle line:84%
that I've talked to, it's
actually a kind of exodus.

00:21:18.550 --> 00:21:25.180 align:middle line:84%
It's a desertion, I think, from
the city, from the metropolis.

00:21:25.180 --> 00:21:29.410 align:middle line:84%
One of the things that drew me
here had to do with a kind of--

00:21:29.410 --> 00:21:34.420 align:middle line:84%
I guess a spirit of autonomy
and self-sufficiency

00:21:34.420 --> 00:21:38.920 align:middle line:90%
and a kind of a slowness.

00:21:38.920 --> 00:21:40.660 align:middle line:84%
Raymond Williams
has this great line

00:21:40.660 --> 00:21:43.900 align:middle line:84%
about the need for
breathing space, places

00:21:43.900 --> 00:21:46.527 align:middle line:84%
that are sort of outside
of the systems of control.

00:21:46.527 --> 00:21:48.860 align:middle line:84%
And I mean, we're never really
outside of those systems.

00:21:48.860 --> 00:21:50.560 align:middle line:84%
But for me, Gabriola
and the islands

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:53.620 align:middle line:84%
have always been a place
where people have assembled

00:21:53.620 --> 00:21:58.300 align:middle line:84%
themselves so that they could
live slowly and in a more

00:21:58.300 --> 00:22:01.990 align:middle line:90%
autonomous, intentional way.

00:22:01.990 --> 00:22:05.290 align:middle line:84%
Slowness allows for
a more aesthetic,

00:22:05.290 --> 00:22:09.130 align:middle line:84%
erotic apprehension of
the world, a kind of grip

00:22:09.130 --> 00:22:09.930 align:middle line:90%
on the world.

00:22:09.930 --> 00:22:27.070 align:middle line:90%


00:22:27.070 --> 00:22:27.870 align:middle line:90%
>> All right.

00:22:27.870 --> 00:22:29.380 align:middle line:90%
So we're working on a pumpkin.

00:22:29.380 --> 00:22:33.193 align:middle line:90%


00:22:33.193 --> 00:22:39.181 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:22:39.181 --> 00:23:29.180 align:middle line:90%


00:23:29.180 --> 00:23:33.860 align:middle line:84%
